![critical](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/critical.svg)

The fallback for generating `id` and `token` values relies on `Date.now()` and `Math.random()`, which are not cryptographically secure. This makes them predictable and exposes a critical denial-of-service (DoS) vulnerability, as an attacker could guess these identifiers and disrupt exports. You must use a cryptographically secure source of randomness, such as `crypto.getRandomValues()`, for the fallback. This same issue applies to the `clientInstanceId` generated in the constructor.

```typescript
    function generateSecureRandomString(length = 16) {
      const arr = new Uint8Array(length);
      globalThis.crypto.getRandomValues(arr);
      return Array.from(arr, byte => byte.toString(16).padStart(2, '0')).join('');
    }

    const id =
      (globalThis.crypto as any)?.randomUUID?.() ??
      `dl-${generateSecureRandomString()}`;
    const token = `tok-${generateSecureRandomString()}`;
```

![high](https://www.gstatic.com/codereviewagent/high-priority.svg)

The current method of building a binary string via repeated concatenation (`binary += ...`) is inefficient and can lead to performance issues and high memory consumption, especially with large blobs. This can be optimized by building an array of string chunks and joining them at the end, which is significantly more performant.

```typescript
      const chunks = [];
      const CHUNK_SIZE = 8192;
      for (let i = 0; i < bytes.length; i += CHUNK_SIZE) {
        chunks.push(String.fromCharCode.apply(null, bytes.subarray(i, i + CHUNK_SIZE)));
      }
      const binary = chunks.join('');
```

